al change. The interviews highlight complex issues in performance art, including the role of identity in performer-audience relationships and art as an exploration of everyday conventions rather than a demonstration of virtuosity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jul 2020) 0aPerformance artxUnited States. 0aPerformance artzUnited States. 0aPerformance artistsxInterviewsxUnited States. 0aPerformance artistszUnited StatesvInterviews. 7aART / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021022640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919662423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520919662.jpg  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles